From 799a5bc37ecea267a4b7af3bdb4a9cc4f6071e4c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: sudm <sudm711@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 3 Jul 2026 16:43:04 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] feat(rollout): chunked action cache with background chunk
 prefetch for sync inference

The sync engine paid the per-tick observation upload + normalization on
every control tick even though ACT consumes the observation only once per
n_action_steps, and the tick that ran the forward pass blocked the control
loop for the full inference latency (a periodic stall of hundreds of ms on
slower accelerators, e.g. ACT at 1080p on Apple MPS).

Two opt-in flags on --inference.type=sync remove both costs:

- chunked_action_cache: drive the policy via predict_action_chunk and serve
  postprocessed actions from a local FIFO, so preprocessing runs once per
  chunk instead of every tick. Validated as behaviour-preserving only for
  ACT without temporal ensembling; the factory raises for other policies.
- prefetch_chunks: compute the next chunk on a background worker once the
  cache drops to prefetch_watermark actions, while the loop keeps serving
  cached actions. The first len(cache-at-snapshot) actions of the new chunk
  are skipped so it stays time-aligned with the ticks served in the
  meantime; if the worker outlasts the runway the engine returns None and
  the robot holds pose (time-shift, same semantics as an inline stall).
  reset() bumps a generation counter so in-flight chunks computed from
  pre-reset observations are discarded, and worker errors propagate to the
  control thread on the next get_action.

Measured on an M1 MacBook driving an SO-101 at 30 FPS with ACT
(chunk_size=100) on a 1920x1080 camera: control-loop compute went from
18.7 ms mean / 1198 ms max per tick to 2.0 ms mean / 76 ms max, with all
forward passes (~180 ms) off the control thread.

Co-authored-by: Cursor <cursoragent@cursor.com>
